00:30:29.164 --> 00:30:31.120
[END PLAYBACK]

00:30:31.120 --> 00:30:32.930
- The plot thickens, right?

00:30:32.930 --> 00:30:36.900
The plot becomes ever
more interesting.

00:30:36.900 --> 00:30:39.050
We also didn't anticipate this.

00:30:39.050 --> 00:30:43.300
We didn't anticipate that it
was going to be another boat

00:30:43.300 --> 00:30:44.140
to rescue Europe.

00:30:47.630 --> 00:30:49.680
These people, by the
way, in the video,

00:30:49.680 --> 00:30:52.130
they are there
with a small boat,

00:30:52.130 --> 00:30:55.060
with megaphones and launching
flares against our boat.

00:30:55.060 --> 00:30:58.190
That's our boat,
the Catania post.

00:30:58.190 --> 00:31:01.650
They did this action against
an MSF boat very quickly.

00:31:01.650 --> 00:31:04.880
We decided just not to
give them the airtime.

00:31:04.880 --> 00:31:08.000
So we didn't really
denounce it or anything.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:10.610
So that was still there.

00:31:10.610 --> 00:31:13.010
Who wants to know
how this ended?

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:15.615
I mean it's--

00:31:15.615 --> 00:31:17.770
It was short lived too.

00:31:17.770 --> 00:31:19.020
Here you go.

00:31:19.020 --> 00:31:21.860
So these guys
crowdfund 50,000 pounds

00:31:21.860 --> 00:31:23.292
to put a boat in the Med.

00:31:23.292 --> 00:31:24.250
They managed to get it.

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:27.770
They chartered a boat called
the C-Star in Djibouti.

00:31:27.770 --> 00:31:29.660
And they start sailing
towards Europe,

00:31:29.660 --> 00:31:32.980
towards the Mediterranean,
trying to stop the NGOs.

00:31:32.980 --> 00:31:38.740
And the irony is of it they
touched land in Cyprus--

00:31:38.740 --> 00:31:42.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:42.100 --> 00:31:45.760
They landed in Cyprus, and
five of their crew members

00:31:45.760 --> 00:31:48.370
who had been recruited--
they were from Sri Lanka,

00:31:48.370 --> 00:31:51.550
they applied for
asylum in Europe.

00:31:51.550 --> 00:31:53.490
So the police gets
on board of the boat,

00:31:53.490 --> 00:31:55.236
and they say, what
are you doing?

00:31:55.236 --> 00:31:57.610
And they find that the rest
of the crew, another other 25

00:31:57.610 --> 00:32:00.640
guys, are also from Sri Lanka,
and they don't have any papers.

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:04.041
So they're taken to court, and
they are deported from Cyprus

00:32:04.041 --> 00:32:04.915
for people smuggling.

00:32:04.915 --> 00:32:08.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:09.540 --> 00:32:10.800
Then they go to Italy.

00:32:10.800 --> 00:32:13.800
In Catania, they face
a canoe demonstration

00:32:13.800 --> 00:32:16.240
by just a bunch of Italians
that get on [INAUDIBLE]..

00:32:16.240 --> 00:32:20.170
They get on the sea and they--

00:32:20.170 --> 00:32:21.695
then they try to get to Tunis.

00:32:21.695 --> 00:32:23.859
And there are Tunisian
fisherman saying

00:32:23.859 --> 00:32:25.150
we don't like this racist boat.

00:32:25.150 --> 00:32:27.910
We don't want it to land here.

00:32:27.910 --> 00:32:32.620
And to add insult to injury,
I think the best part of this,

00:32:32.620 --> 00:32:34.650
they get an engine
break down, and they

00:32:34.650 --> 00:32:36.300
had to be rescued
by one of the NGOs

00:32:36.300 --> 00:32:37.591
they were trying to bring down.

00:32:37.591 --> 00:32:40.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:41.690 --> 00:32:42.270
It's funny.

00:32:42.270 --> 00:32:46.770
We laughed a lot at the time
when Defend Europe went down.

00:32:46.770 --> 00:32:47.940
There was social media.

00:32:47.940 --> 00:32:49.710
We had a bit of a
laugh with these guys.

00:32:49.710 --> 00:32:54.150
But what they were saying
really condensed some discourse

00:32:54.150 --> 00:32:57.540
that was really installing
itself in the narrative.

00:32:57.540 --> 00:32:59.030
They were not alone.

00:32:59.030 --> 00:33:00.600
These are young
people around Europe.

00:33:00.600 --> 00:33:02.290
They are not that important.

00:33:02.290 --> 00:33:05.640
But what they say
echoes with many people.

00:33:05.640 --> 00:33:07.770
So they had to do something.

00:33:07.770 --> 00:33:11.520
Imagine yourself, you're
a European prime minister.

00:33:11.520 --> 00:33:13.080
You have the MSF
of the world saying

00:33:13.080 --> 00:33:13.870
you have to rescue people.

00:33:13.870 --> 00:33:15.745
You have to open safe
and legal alternatives.

00:33:15.745 --> 00:33:20.620
And you have these other people
saying stop the invasion.

00:33:20.620 --> 00:33:21.580
So what do you do?

00:33:21.580 --> 00:33:23.570
You cannot agree
within yourselves.

00:33:23.570 --> 00:33:25.390
When people arrive--

00:33:25.390 --> 00:33:27.010
Italy's saying we
need to be helped.

00:33:27.010 --> 00:33:29.500
The other countries need to
be taking immigrants as well,

00:33:29.500 --> 00:33:30.220
and we need to distribute.

00:33:30.220 --> 00:33:32.719
The other countries all want
to look in the other direction.

00:33:32.719 --> 00:33:33.900
The Italians say why us?

00:33:33.900 --> 00:33:35.560
Greece the same.

00:33:35.560 --> 00:33:36.340
So what do you do?

00:33:36.340 --> 00:33:37.210
You cannot fix that.

00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:41.350
You have Greek camps that
really look appalling.

00:33:41.350 --> 00:33:44.200
Some of the worst
camps I ever seen.

00:33:44.200 --> 00:33:45.940
You have people at the fences.

00:33:45.940 --> 00:33:47.390
You have all the coverage.

00:33:47.390 --> 00:33:48.640
So what do you do?

00:33:48.640 --> 00:33:50.490
You pass the buck.

00:33:50.490 --> 00:33:52.600
The magic bullet.

00:33:52.600 --> 00:33:55.750
That was the first group
photo of European politicians

00:33:55.750 --> 00:33:56.965
throughout the crisis.

00:33:56.965 --> 00:33:58.090
There were going to be two.

00:33:58.090 --> 00:33:58.990
That was a first one.

00:33:58.990 --> 00:34:01.406
The first time they actually
managed to agree and announce

00:34:01.406 --> 00:34:02.020
something.

00:34:02.020 --> 00:34:03.640
And the announcement
was that they

00:34:03.640 --> 00:34:08.440
have got Turkey to agree on
taking the refugees back.

00:34:08.440 --> 00:34:10.840
How much would it
cost for Turkey

00:34:10.840 --> 00:34:12.520
to agree to take
the refugees that

00:34:12.520 --> 00:34:16.090
have crossed to Greece
and to Eastern Europe

00:34:16.090 --> 00:34:19.960
back into Turkey,
control their border,

00:34:19.960 --> 00:34:22.540
and prevent further
departure of boats?

00:34:22.540 --> 00:34:24.370
What do we need to give them?

00:34:24.370 --> 00:34:25.199
It was easy.

00:34:25.199 --> 00:34:28.750
It was $6 billion
euros over three years.

00:34:28.750 --> 00:34:33.130
And the problem is that the
Turkish citizens will have easy

00:34:33.130 --> 00:34:37.449
access to Europe through a
quicker system getting visas

00:34:37.449 --> 00:34:39.770
or a visa-free--

00:34:39.770 --> 00:34:42.100
And once all this was
sorted, maybe there

00:34:42.100 --> 00:34:45.070
was going to be
a orderly program

00:34:45.070 --> 00:34:47.889
to resettle some of the Syrian
refugees that had arrived back

00:34:47.889 --> 00:34:52.120
into Europe once they determine
how that was going to--

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:55.760
Very few of those things
actually remained fulfilled.

00:34:55.760 --> 00:34:58.592
But that was what can
we do if we don't agree,

00:34:58.592 --> 00:34:59.800
and we don't want the people?

00:34:59.800 --> 00:35:01.330
We just pass it back
to something else.

00:35:01.330 --> 00:35:02.110
Just push it out.

00:35:05.990 --> 00:35:11.640
By the way, that moment is
when we knew we were losing.

00:35:11.640 --> 00:35:13.270
We knew we had no traction.

00:35:13.270 --> 00:35:15.740
But that moment we knew
that there was no hope.

00:35:15.740 --> 00:35:17.540
We were meeting with
all those people.

00:35:17.540 --> 00:35:19.490
We had access to those people.

00:35:19.490 --> 00:35:25.800
We had a powerful campaign going
on with other organizations.

00:35:25.800 --> 00:35:30.260
We had media coverage,
everything we wanted with it.

00:35:30.260 --> 00:35:31.670
But we were getting no traction.

00:35:31.670 --> 00:35:34.985
The solution was not going
to come by rescuing people

00:35:34.985 --> 00:35:36.410
or providing better conditions.

00:35:36.410 --> 00:35:37.060
Europe, no.

00:35:37.060 --> 00:35:38.810
The solution was to
pass the buck outside.

00:35:38.810 --> 00:35:40.580
So at that moment we knew.

00:35:40.580 --> 00:35:43.500
This is lost, and
search and rescue

00:35:43.500 --> 00:35:46.930
is on the way to being
terminated as well.

00:35:46.930 --> 00:35:47.430
Why?

00:35:47.430 --> 00:35:51.760
Because if you want people
to really remain in Libya,

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:54.490
you cannot have NGOs rescuing
people and bringing them

00:35:54.490 --> 00:35:54.990
to Italy.

00:35:54.990 --> 00:35:56.730
There's no way
you can have that.

00:35:56.730 --> 00:35:58.600
So we knew we were an obstacle.

00:35:58.600 --> 00:36:01.260
What we said is keep going.

00:36:01.260 --> 00:36:02.610
There are two things we can go.

00:36:02.610 --> 00:36:04.109
We're not going to
stop voluntarily.

00:36:04.109 --> 00:36:07.290
Just keep going and let's
see if they stop us.

00:36:07.290 --> 00:36:09.890
And let's expand our
operations into Libya.

00:36:09.890 --> 00:36:10.830
And why Libya?

00:36:10.830 --> 00:36:14.100
I'm going to tell you
this very quickly.

00:36:14.100 --> 00:36:15.480
We had been talking
to the people

00:36:15.480 --> 00:36:17.880
we have rescued for
two years by then.

00:36:17.880 --> 00:36:20.940
And they were telling us about
horrible conditions in Libya.

00:36:20.940 --> 00:36:23.402
People were arbitrarily
retained, extorted for money.

00:36:23.402 --> 00:36:25.110
There were stories
about sexual violence.

00:36:25.110 --> 00:36:26.560
There were stories
about torture.

00:36:26.560 --> 00:36:28.440
There were stories about
overcrowded prisons.

00:36:28.440 --> 00:36:33.170
There were stories about the
appalling living conditions,

00:36:33.170 --> 00:36:36.922
no proper water, no
food, no sanitation.

00:36:36.922 --> 00:36:38.880
So we had been discussing
this for a long time.

00:36:38.880 --> 00:36:40.840
Can we actually do
something about that?

00:36:40.840 --> 00:36:44.670
And the same with sea, it
was like how do we do that?

00:36:44.670 --> 00:36:45.990
There was no witnesses.

00:36:45.990 --> 00:36:48.360
Jordans didn't get visas
to enter into Libya.

00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:51.090
Only a few people had
managed to sneak in by then.

00:36:51.090 --> 00:36:53.730
And we said, OK, [INAUDIBLE]
are also not going there.

00:36:53.730 --> 00:36:56.460
Can we actually negotiate
access so they are involved.

00:36:56.460 --> 00:36:59.380
Let's negotiate with
the Libyan people

00:36:59.380 --> 00:37:01.480
managing detention centers.

00:37:01.480 --> 00:37:02.350
Can we work there?

00:37:02.350 --> 00:37:05.520
Why would they
allow us to do that?

00:37:05.520 --> 00:37:11.850
So could we convince them that
we can go and serve a purpose?

00:37:11.850 --> 00:37:15.000
Let's agree to be used to
improve detention conditions.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.700
Because we could do something
for the people of Libya.

00:37:17.700 --> 00:37:20.070
We could actually improve
food, improve water,

00:37:20.070 --> 00:37:22.209
improve sanitation.

00:37:22.209 --> 00:37:23.750
But at the same
time, we're not going

00:37:23.750 --> 00:37:25.249
to do it at the
price of not showing

00:37:25.249 --> 00:37:27.187
what's going on in there.

00:37:27.187 --> 00:37:29.520
So we wanted to really use
that presence to bear witness

00:37:29.520 --> 00:37:31.640
with what was going on.

00:37:31.640 --> 00:37:33.334
And can we keep our team safe?

00:37:33.334 --> 00:37:34.750
When we are at
sea, you're at sea.

00:37:34.750 --> 00:37:37.360
But if in Libya, you get
kidnapped in two minutes.

00:37:37.360 --> 00:37:39.180
You get a death
threat, and you're out.

00:37:39.180 --> 00:37:43.000
You get one staff
killed and you're out.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:44.440
So that was a bit
of a trade off.

00:37:44.440 --> 00:37:46.480
Can we actually do this safely?

00:37:46.480 --> 00:37:50.170
We decided to go with it and
with accepting that challenge.

00:37:50.170 --> 00:37:53.230
How do you actually
operate there

00:37:53.230 --> 00:37:57.170
without being co-opted into
a white-washing exercise?

00:37:57.170 --> 00:37:58.450
Now you are there.

00:37:58.450 --> 00:38:00.852
Yes, you can feed
people properly.

00:38:00.852 --> 00:38:02.810
You can give them proper
water, and say there's

00:38:02.810 --> 00:38:03.847
your medical care.

00:38:03.847 --> 00:38:05.680
What are you going to
do when they bring you

00:38:05.680 --> 00:38:08.920
the same person twice
with wounds that

00:38:08.920 --> 00:38:10.479
are consistent with torture?

00:38:10.479 --> 00:38:11.770
Are you going to say something?

00:38:11.770 --> 00:38:14.830
Or are you just going
to put a patch again?

00:38:14.830 --> 00:38:17.020
So we started this very
difficult relationship

00:38:17.020 --> 00:38:19.810
with the legal authorities,
but they allowed us to be in.

00:38:19.810 --> 00:38:21.880
And it was very,
very, very tense

00:38:21.880 --> 00:38:25.540
and very difficult to
manage that operation.

00:38:25.540 --> 00:38:29.980
So we launched
this in June 2016.

00:38:29.980 --> 00:38:33.280
Just a few months
later or a year later,

00:38:33.280 --> 00:38:36.640
the second group shot came
from the European leaders.

00:38:36.640 --> 00:38:39.580
They had managed to find a
deal again to pass the buck.

00:38:39.580 --> 00:38:41.980
Let's work with the Libyans
to make sure that people

00:38:41.980 --> 00:38:43.960
don't depart from the shores.

00:38:43.960 --> 00:38:46.420
And Libya was much more
difficult than Turkey.

00:38:46.420 --> 00:38:47.920
You can't talk to
Erdogan in Turkey.

00:38:47.920 --> 00:38:50.890
Erdogan sort of controls
Turkey pretty well.

00:38:50.890 --> 00:38:53.940
In Libya, there are
different factions.

00:38:53.940 --> 00:38:57.520
It was much more
difficult to control that.

00:38:57.520 --> 00:38:58.420
And they had to--

00:38:58.420 --> 00:39:01.920
how are you going to really
prevent people from going?

00:39:01.920 --> 00:39:06.820
And what they said at that
point was this mixed discourse.

00:39:06.820 --> 00:39:08.500
Let me read it
because I get confused

00:39:08.500 --> 00:39:09.240
when I read these things.

00:39:09.240 --> 00:39:11.198
"With hundreds already
having lost their lives,

00:39:11.198 --> 00:39:13.960
the EU is determined to
take additional measures

00:39:13.960 --> 00:39:15.520
to reduce migratory flows."

00:39:15.520 --> 00:39:19.330
So the notion is like let's make
sure that more lives are not

00:39:19.330 --> 00:39:21.240
lost at sea.

00:39:21.240 --> 00:39:23.620
Let's keep them there.

00:39:23.620 --> 00:39:25.500
If they don't get on
boats, they don't drown.

00:39:25.500 --> 00:39:26.570
Right?

00:39:26.570 --> 00:39:27.836
Pretty simple.

00:39:27.836 --> 00:39:30.105
Whose crisis are
we trying to solve?

00:39:33.020 --> 00:39:34.810
So Europe under threats.

00:39:34.810 --> 00:39:38.220
That media-- that was the
total of the reporting by them.

00:39:38.220 --> 00:39:41.500
And who are those guys in there?

00:39:41.500 --> 00:39:44.950
That's the EU funding and
training the Libyan Coast Guard

00:39:44.950 --> 00:39:46.220
to intercept and return.

00:39:46.220 --> 00:39:48.006
So search and rescue came.

00:39:48.006 --> 00:39:49.630
The plan was let's
get rid of the NGOs.

00:39:49.630 --> 00:39:51.430
Hand it over to the
Libyans to make sure

00:39:51.430 --> 00:39:54.230
that they search, they rescue.

00:39:54.230 --> 00:39:57.300
You see the caption there?

00:39:57.300 --> 00:39:59.930
They are rescued
to be brought back.

00:39:59.930 --> 00:40:03.670
So it's an interception
and return operation.

00:40:03.670 --> 00:40:07.120
We knew our boats at sea
had very little time to go.

00:40:10.530 --> 00:40:12.390
We decided to, OK,
let's go all out.

00:40:12.390 --> 00:40:17.760
We had a report, let's go all
out accusing the EU of funding

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:19.230
torture in Libya.

00:40:19.230 --> 00:40:20.860
We did everything we could.

00:40:20.860 --> 00:40:23.490
I mean this is just one example.

00:40:23.490 --> 00:40:25.770
And we, of course, tried
to facilitate media

00:40:25.770 --> 00:40:27.150
reporting as much as we could.

00:40:27.150 --> 00:40:27.816
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:40:27.816 --> 00:40:29.370
- At this detention
center in Surman,

00:40:29.370 --> 00:40:32.310
an eerie silence prevails.

00:40:32.310 --> 00:40:34.980
Most of the 250 young
women here tried

00:40:34.980 --> 00:40:38.440
to cross the Mediterranean
to reach Europe,

00:40:38.440 --> 00:40:41.520
but they didn't make it.

00:40:41.520 --> 00:40:43.890
Cynthia from Nigeria
was in a boat that

00:40:43.890 --> 00:40:46.061
was stopped by security forces.

00:40:46.061 --> 00:40:47.310
They brought her to this camp.

00:40:47.310 --> 00:40:50.010
- [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:40:50.010 --> 00:40:51.840
- She says they
were caught at sea,

00:40:51.840 --> 00:40:54.060
and their boat
came under gunfire,

00:40:54.060 --> 00:40:55.980
and that it's God's
will that she survived.

00:40:59.130 --> 00:41:01.770
Cynthia was heavily
pregnant at the time.

00:41:01.770 --> 00:41:04.590
Today, she has to use the
detention center toilet

00:41:04.590 --> 00:41:06.600
to change her baby's diapers.

00:41:06.600 --> 00:41:10.506
And she doesn't know if
the child will survive.

00:41:10.506 --> 00:41:12.100
- [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:41:12.100 --> 00:41:14.400
- She says she can't nurse
her daughter because she's

00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:19.470
been unable to produce any milk
since her daughter's birth.

00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:21.840
German diplomats have
compared the conditions

00:41:21.840 --> 00:41:27.150
in many Libyan detention centers
to Nazi concentration camps.

00:41:27.150 --> 00:41:29.460
They've just gone public
with their report which

00:41:29.460 --> 00:41:34.588
says the young women are often
beaten and raped by the staff.

00:41:34.588 --> 00:41:36.324
- There is no phone here.

00:41:36.324 --> 00:41:39.930
Since five months, I have not
spoken to my parents, nobody.

00:41:39.930 --> 00:41:42.753
We are just here.

00:41:42.753 --> 00:41:48.498
- What we are begging them for
[INAUDIBLE] That is all we need

00:41:48.498 --> 00:41:50.690
here.

00:41:50.690 --> 00:41:52.530
- The managing
staff in some camps

00:41:52.530 --> 00:41:56.020
are even accused of
human trafficking.

00:41:56.020 --> 00:41:58.560
The camp director in
Surman disputes this.

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:02.799
He accuses western countries
of ignoring the horror.

00:42:02.799 --> 00:42:06.010
- [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:42:06.510 --> 00:42:10.680
- Reporters show the problems
and the poor conditions here,

00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:13.330
but no one is stepping
up to help us.

00:42:13.330 --> 00:42:14.580
We're not getting any support.

00:42:14.580 --> 00:42:17.811
- [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:42:18.310 --> 00:42:21.180
- The staff says medical
aid is urgently needed

00:42:21.180 --> 00:42:22.950
at this detention center.

00:42:22.950 --> 00:42:25.110
But even if it's
delivered, no one

00:42:25.110 --> 00:42:28.760
believes that will make
much of a difference.

00:42:28.760 --> 00:42:31.110
[END PLAYBACK]

00:42:31.110 --> 00:42:32.040
- That was it.

00:42:32.040 --> 00:42:33.171
The game is very clear.

00:42:33.171 --> 00:42:34.670
Libya is saying,
just give us money.

00:42:34.670 --> 00:42:35.900
We'll detain people properly.

00:42:35.900 --> 00:42:37.720
We'll improve conditions.

00:42:37.720 --> 00:42:39.560
Today, you have
UNHCR working there.

00:42:39.560 --> 00:42:41.690
You have the IOM.

00:42:41.690 --> 00:42:46.310
That's how aid is being used
today to just prop this up.

00:42:46.310 --> 00:42:48.440
The question for me is
not whether to provide aid

00:42:48.440 --> 00:42:49.070
there or not.

00:42:49.070 --> 00:42:51.800
The question is at what
price do you provide aid

00:42:51.800 --> 00:42:53.700
and how critical
you remain for this?

00:42:53.700 --> 00:42:56.685
And how do you
make that balance?

00:43:00.036 --> 00:43:01.160
And this is the last slide.

00:43:01.160 --> 00:43:03.870
I have two more minutes to go.

00:43:03.870 --> 00:43:05.280
Last couple of slides.

00:43:05.280 --> 00:43:08.220
So the last step was
very clear to everyone.

00:43:08.220 --> 00:43:09.870
Let's get rid of the NGOs.

00:43:09.870 --> 00:43:11.404
So it was a quick succession.

00:43:11.404 --> 00:43:13.320
There was a smear campaign
very, very quickly.

00:43:13.320 --> 00:43:15.780
It's like the
water taxis, it was

00:43:15.780 --> 00:43:17.550
installed by Italian
politicians saying,

00:43:17.550 --> 00:43:19.980
OK, these water taxis
are bringing the illegals

00:43:19.980 --> 00:43:20.784
into Europe.

00:43:20.784 --> 00:43:22.200
They are colluding
with smugglers.

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:24.660
You heard what the guys from
Defend Europe were doing.

00:43:24.660 --> 00:43:25.760
That really got traction.

00:43:28.270 --> 00:43:31.600
There were prosecutions
again to NGOs.

00:43:31.600 --> 00:43:32.860
They didn't prosecute us.

00:43:32.860 --> 00:43:39.100
But the smaller NGOs that had
been born for a single purpose,

00:43:39.100 --> 00:43:43.300
to rescue people
at sea for this,

00:43:43.300 --> 00:43:47.320
were really affected by both
the credibility issue of being

00:43:47.320 --> 00:43:49.150
cooperating with smugglers.

00:43:49.150 --> 00:43:53.710
Their funding went like this,
and some of them disappeared.

00:43:53.710 --> 00:43:56.170
The rest had their
boats impounded at sea,

00:43:56.170 --> 00:43:58.750
at Italian ports and
in Malta in Italy.

00:43:58.750 --> 00:44:00.332
Some of the boats
are still there.

00:44:00.332 --> 00:44:01.290
Some people prosecuted.

00:44:01.290 --> 00:44:03.632
Nobody has been
condemned for anything.

00:44:03.632 --> 00:44:04.840
There's very little evidence.

00:44:04.840 --> 00:44:06.089
There's been a massive effort.

00:44:06.089 --> 00:44:09.050
There's been intelligence
agents infiltrating

00:44:09.050 --> 00:44:10.490
on some of the NGO boats.

00:44:10.490 --> 00:44:14.710
Even satellite eavesdropping
interception of calls.

00:44:14.710 --> 00:44:16.900
There's been a massive
intelligence effort

00:44:16.900 --> 00:44:19.990
to just try to prosecute
the people that

00:44:19.990 --> 00:44:20.921
were rescued at sea.

00:44:23.570 --> 00:44:26.360
Then intervention from
the Libyan Coast Guard.

00:44:26.360 --> 00:44:28.400
The instances of the
Libyan Coast Guard

00:44:28.400 --> 00:44:31.160
coming and threatening
NGO boats on the radio,

00:44:31.160 --> 00:44:34.310
opening fire on an
MSF boat or other.

00:44:34.310 --> 00:44:35.809
[INAUDIBLE] are well-documented.

00:44:35.809 --> 00:44:36.850
You can just Google them.

00:44:36.850 --> 00:44:37.850
They're all out there.

00:44:37.850 --> 00:44:39.740
We all denounced
this as it happened.

00:44:39.740 --> 00:44:43.680
The Libyan Coast Guard
got increasingly violent.

00:44:43.680 --> 00:44:45.830
And we all got a
letter-- all the NGOs

00:44:45.830 --> 00:44:48.120
from their coordination
in Rome, saying, sorry,

00:44:48.120 --> 00:44:51.740
we can no longer guarantee
your security at sea.

00:44:51.740 --> 00:44:55.020
So the message was clear.

00:44:55.020 --> 00:44:57.170
By the summer of 2018,
there was one boat.

00:44:57.170 --> 00:44:59.930
From the 10, we went
back to one boat.

00:44:59.930 --> 00:45:01.349
And that was our boat.

00:45:01.349 --> 00:45:02.265
That was the Aquarius.

00:45:05.695 --> 00:45:07.070
The big boat in
the background is

00:45:07.070 --> 00:45:09.250
the Aquarius, that orange boat.

00:45:09.250 --> 00:45:13.600
That was the last
boat standing by 2018.

00:45:13.600 --> 00:45:17.230
That's when Matteo Salvini gets
elected in Italy on this slogan

00:45:17.230 --> 00:45:19.160
of stop the invasion.

00:45:19.160 --> 00:45:20.920
There's an invasion
taking place.

00:45:20.920 --> 00:45:22.820
Italians first.

00:45:22.820 --> 00:45:29.284
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH] Italians
first, stop the invasion.

00:45:29.284 --> 00:45:30.700
The succession for
this-- and this

00:45:30.700 --> 00:45:35.520
is since I was leaving my
job and I came to Radcliffe,

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:37.670
all this happened
over the summer.

00:45:37.670 --> 00:45:41.910
You got June 2018,
we had rescued

00:45:41.910 --> 00:45:45.490
629 people were not allowed
to dock in Italy anymore.

00:45:45.490 --> 00:45:48.520
The ship was adrift
at sea for a week

00:45:48.520 --> 00:45:50.725
until we managed to get
an offer from Valencia.

00:45:50.725 --> 00:45:52.450
We had to go all
the way to Spain

00:45:52.450 --> 00:45:55.420
to be able to disembark people.

00:45:55.420 --> 00:45:58.740
In August 2018,
again another rescue.

00:45:58.740 --> 00:46:04.050
We were not allowed to disembark
anywhere, not even in Valencia.

00:46:04.050 --> 00:46:07.880
In August 2018, we were
sailing under a Gibraltar flag.

00:46:07.880 --> 00:46:11.030
Under the UK pressure, that
flag was stripped from the ship.

00:46:11.030 --> 00:46:13.970
So the ship was
without registration.

00:46:13.970 --> 00:46:14.850
We took three weeks.

00:46:14.850 --> 00:46:17.480
We registered again the boat
under the Panamanian flag,

00:46:17.480 --> 00:46:21.200
the only country that
would give us a flag.

00:46:21.200 --> 00:46:24.170
In September, we did another
rescue, over 58 people

00:46:24.170 --> 00:46:25.784
on board.

00:46:25.784 --> 00:46:27.450
They told us, you
cannot disembark here.

00:46:27.450 --> 00:46:29.870
You have to hand over people
to Libyan Coast Guard.

00:46:29.870 --> 00:46:31.520
We said, no way we're
going to do that.

00:46:31.520 --> 00:46:32.390
We keep people on board.

00:46:32.390 --> 00:46:33.890
We know where people
are going back.

00:46:33.890 --> 00:46:36.720
We cannot possibly do that.

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:38.770
So our flag was stripped again.

00:46:38.770 --> 00:46:42.470
Italy put pressure on Panama,
and the second flag was--

00:46:42.470 --> 00:46:44.290
the ship today
doesn't have a flag.

00:46:44.290 --> 00:46:46.840
There's a campaign
running to [INAUDIBLE]..

00:46:46.840 --> 00:46:49.520
There is no state that
has been willing to put

00:46:49.520 --> 00:46:52.610
a flag on that ship, so the
operation is virtually halted.

00:46:52.610 --> 00:46:53.690
The ship is on port.

00:46:57.370 --> 00:46:59.770
What Mary had said,
in three years

00:46:59.770 --> 00:47:03.490
there were around 425
operations by MSF alone.

00:47:03.490 --> 00:47:07.626
77,000 people
assisted in our boats.

00:47:07.626 --> 00:47:10.880
Today, there are no search
and rescue boats in the Med.

00:47:10.880 --> 00:47:16.330
So far 2000 people have died
in the Med this year alone.

00:47:16.330 --> 00:47:19.187
And of course arrivals
in Italy have reduced.

00:47:19.187 --> 00:47:21.020
They are probably being
taken back to Libya.

00:47:25.730 --> 00:47:29.072
What does this is little
story mean for us?

00:47:29.072 --> 00:47:30.780
What does this story
of search and rescue

00:47:30.780 --> 00:47:33.250
mean for us in the Med?

00:47:33.250 --> 00:47:36.550
What does it say
about the way we

00:47:36.550 --> 00:47:38.530
frame this crisis, how
we conceptualize it,

00:47:38.530 --> 00:47:40.150
how we think of it?

00:47:43.794 --> 00:47:45.460
There are a couple
of questions that I'm

00:47:45.460 --> 00:47:46.418
exploring at Radcliffe.

00:47:46.418 --> 00:47:47.850
And this is very, very raw.

00:47:47.850 --> 00:47:50.257
There's no much
thinking about it.

00:47:50.257 --> 00:47:52.590
But these are the questions
that strike me as important.

00:47:52.590 --> 00:47:54.157
How do we frame this problem?

00:47:54.157 --> 00:47:55.240
How do we talk about this?

00:47:55.240 --> 00:47:57.750
How do we talk about them?

00:47:57.750 --> 00:48:02.430
We talk about them as
an undifferentiated mass

00:48:02.430 --> 00:48:04.530
of people.

00:48:04.530 --> 00:48:07.050
We talk about them
as a natural disaster

00:48:07.050 --> 00:48:11.580
that is about to strike us,
that it's a threat that we

00:48:11.580 --> 00:48:13.440
need to defend ourselves from.

00:48:16.320 --> 00:48:20.910
How does this language that
we use to talk about them

00:48:20.910 --> 00:48:24.300
allow us to dehumanize
people and strip them

00:48:24.300 --> 00:48:27.680
from any attributes
that would actually

00:48:27.680 --> 00:48:29.420
question what we are doing?

00:48:33.246 --> 00:48:34.870
I couldn't resist
putting this this big

00:48:34.870 --> 00:48:37.560
because it's from this morning.

00:48:37.560 --> 00:48:40.567
With this crisis, not what
do we talk about them,

00:48:40.567 --> 00:48:41.650
what does it say about us?

00:48:41.650 --> 00:48:43.840
That's much more
interesting, right?

00:48:43.840 --> 00:48:46.770
What does it say about us, how
we're framing the immigration

00:48:46.770 --> 00:48:48.090
problem?

00:48:48.090 --> 00:48:50.170
When we other people--

00:48:50.170 --> 00:48:53.490
when we define the other--
when a group of insiders

00:48:53.490 --> 00:48:57.450
decides that the other is
the threat and the enemy.

00:48:57.450 --> 00:48:58.890
We know that trick, right?

00:48:58.890 --> 00:49:00.990
We saw it throughout history.

00:49:00.990 --> 00:49:03.060
We don't need to be
lazy to think oh, what

00:49:03.060 --> 00:49:05.310
about Germany 1930s?

00:49:05.310 --> 00:49:07.630
We had the Jewish question.

00:49:07.630 --> 00:49:10.350
Now we have
immigration question.

00:49:10.350 --> 00:49:16.510
We don't need to go to how
Jim Crow's America defined

00:49:16.510 --> 00:49:17.410
the Negro problem.

00:49:19.940 --> 00:49:22.310
That said, much more
as James Baldwin said,

00:49:22.310 --> 00:49:28.520
that said much more about white
America and African-Americans.

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:34.265
What does this say about
how we think about people

00:49:34.265 --> 00:49:37.250
and who we are today?

00:49:37.250 --> 00:49:40.610
Here in Europe or in Australia.

00:49:40.610 --> 00:49:42.770
This guy there is saying
we need a final solution

00:49:42.770 --> 00:49:44.330
to the immigration problem--

00:49:44.330 --> 00:49:47.660
to the Muslim
immigration problem.

00:49:47.660 --> 00:49:49.730
Then these people.

00:49:49.730 --> 00:49:52.520
Isn't it much more
dangerous this retreat

00:49:52.520 --> 00:49:57.290
into ethnic nationalism,
tribalism, hate?

00:49:57.290 --> 00:50:01.050
That kind of speech
makes Sweden great again.

00:50:01.050 --> 00:50:03.200
Isn't it much,
much more dangerous

00:50:03.200 --> 00:50:07.510
than openness to the world?

00:50:07.510 --> 00:50:13.980
How do we define a notion
of us that transcends

00:50:13.980 --> 00:50:17.990
barbed wire, border
walls, ghettos,

00:50:17.990 --> 00:50:21.500
and has a more egalitarian
and humanist aspiration?

00:50:21.500 --> 00:50:24.130
Can we do that?

00:50:24.130 --> 00:50:26.600
Shouldn't we try?

00:50:26.600 --> 00:50:30.610
What are our values in
these turbulent times?

00:50:30.610 --> 00:50:32.640
What are we doing?

00:50:32.640 --> 00:50:37.770
Can we afford to be
indifferent and at what price?

00:50:37.770 --> 00:50:39.270
Thank you for listening.

00:50:39.270 --> 00:50:41.070
[APPLAUSE]

00:50:41.070 --> 00:50:44.120
[MUSIC PLAYING]

